sentence: Benchmarks closed in the red on Tuesday following mixed earnings results and renewed concerns about the state of China's economy.
These factors outweighed encouraging housing starts data.
The blue-chip index's three-day run of gains came to close following disappointing results from Wal-Mart.
Meanwhile, fears surrounding China dragged down commodity stocks which led the declining stocks for the day.

For a look at the issues currently facing the markets, make sure to read today's Ahead of Wall Street article

The Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJI) lost 0.2% to close at 17,511.34.The Standard & Poor's 500 (S&P 500) declined 0.3% to 2,096.92.
The tech-laden Nasdaq Composite Index closed at 5,059.35, losing 0.6%.
The fear-gauge CBOE Volatility Index (VIX) increased 5.9% to settle at 13.79.
A total of around 5.4 billion shares were traded on Friday, lower than the month-to-date average of 6.7 billion.
Decliners outpaced advancing stocks on the NYSE.
For 63% stocks that declined, 34% advanced.
The two major earnings reports of the day came from key Dow components Wal-Mart Stores Inc. ( WMT ) and The Home Depot, Inc. ( HD ).
Wal-Mart's fiscal second quarter 2016 earnings of $1.08 per share missed the Zacks Consensus Estimate of $1.12.
Additionally, earnings per share for fiscal 2016 are now expected to be in the range of $4.40 - $4.70, down from the previous guidance of $4.70 - $5.05.
Shares of Wal-Mart lost 3.4% to $69.49, the lowest level experienced in around two and a half years.
This led to a 16.2 point loss for the blue-chip index.
In contrast, Home Depot posted second-quarter adjusted earnings of $1.71 per share, which increased 12.5% from the year-ago quarter and beat the Zacks Consensus Estimate by a penny.
The company also raised its outlook for full fiscal year.
The company now projects sales growth of 5.2%-6% compared with 4.2%-4.8% expected earlier.
Shares of Home Depot gained 2.6%.
Meanwhile, concerns surrounding China's economy weighed on the markets, particularly commodity stocks.
The Shanghai Composite Index slumped 6.1%, closing only 240 points higher than the low it touched on Jul 8.
Stocks in China declined despite a record injection of funds in a day in more than one and a half years.
The decline triggered fears of a further devaluation in yuan, leading to losses for basic materials.
Mixed results and concerns about China negated the positive impact of bullish housing starts data.
Housing starts increased 0.2% in July to 1,206,000 units, the largest figure witnessed since Oct 2007.
Additionally, the estimate for June was revised sharply upward to 1,204,000 from the original figure of 1,174,000.
However, building permits declined significantly, by 16.3% to 1,119,000 in July.
Developments in China led to The Materials Select Sector SPDR ETF (XLB) declining 0.7% and emerging as the biggest decliner among the S&P 500 sectors.

Key stocks from the sector including Freeport-McMoRan Inc. ( FCX ), E. I. du Pont de Nemours and Company ( DD ), Monsanto Company ( MON ), The Dow Chemical Company ( DOW ), Praxair Inc. ( PX ) and LyondellBasell Industries N.V. ( LYB ) decreased 3.1%, 0.7%, 0.6%, 1.6%, 0.4% and 1.3%, respectively.
Overall, 8 out of 10 sectors of the S&P 500 ended in the red.
Of the two gainers, the Consumer Discretionary Select Sector SPDR ETF (XLY) increased only 0.1%.
However, the Homebuilders ETF (XHB) increased significantly, gaining 1.2% on housing starts data.

Key stocks from the sector including Lennar Corporation ( LEN ), DR Horton Inc. ( DHI ), PulteGroup, Inc. ( PHM ), Owens Corning ( OC ) and NVR, Inc. ( NVR ) gained 3.1%, 1.4%, 2.5%, 0.7% and 0.6%, respectively.
